  , issueTitle =
      "[Question of Java Client]: Should LocalDateTime be saved with time zone information?"
  , issuePullRequest = Nothing
  , issueUrl =
      "https://api.github.com/repos/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/issues/5487"
  , issueCreatedAt = 2016 (-03) (-07) 03 : 33 : 11 UTC
  , issueBody =
      Just
        "I have a trivial question about Java Client Driver of RethinkDB.\nI am working on [Support almost ALL types in/out. (e.x. Enum, OffsetDateTime, BigDecimal, double, Float... ) by QianJin2013 \183 Pull Request #5484 \183 rethinkdb/rethinkdb](https://github.com/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/pull/5484), it's too long, so i ask it here separately.\n\nFirst, let me give some summary about Java's new Date Time type design:\n--------Type-------------------------   ----have time zone----   ----RethinkDB save time zone----  \n`java.time.OffsetDateTime`:             YES                                 YES\n`java.time.TimeZonedDateTime`:     YES                                 YES\n`java.time.LocalDateTime`:               NO                                 YES           !!Not consistent\n`java.time.LocalDate`:                       NO                                 NO\n`java.time.LocalTime`:                      NO                                 NO\n\nThen, i'd thought when rethink db's java client store above types to db, it follow above policy. But in fact NO.\n\nWhen i store `OffsetDateTime` to db, it save data as following format:\n\n```\n    \"offsetDateTimeProperty\": {\n        \"$reql_type$\": \"TIME\",\n        \"epoch_time\": 1457175284.443,\n        \"timezone\": \"+09:00\"\n    },\n```\n\nThis is perfect.\n\nBut when i store `LocalDateTime` to db, it will try to output time zone information:\nThe <a href=\"https://github.com/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/blob/next/drivers/java/src/main/java/com/rethinkdb/ast/Util.java#L87\">ast.Util.java:: toReqlAst  convert  `LocalDateTime` or `LocalTime` to OffsetDateTime.</a>\n\n```\n            ZoneId zid = ZoneId.systemDefault();\n            DateTimeFormatter fmt2 = fmt.withZone(zid);\n            return Iso8601.fromString(((LocalDateTime) val).format(fmt2));\n```\n\nThis also sounds reasonable. So, having fixed the bug of .format() error with \n\n```\n            ZonedDateTime zdt = ((LocalDateTime)val).atZone(ZoneId.systemDefault());\n            return Iso8601.fromString(zdt.format(fmt));\n```\n\nThe LocalDateTime will be output as following format (same as OffsetDateTime):\n\n```\n    \"localDateTimeProperty\": {\n        \"$reql_type$\": \"TIME\",\n        \"epoch_time\": 1457175284.444,\n        \"timezone\": \"+09:00\"\n    },\n```\n\nAnd for `LocalDate`, it stores as different format, without time zone information. (I do not know where did the conversion yet).\n\n```\n    \"localDateProperty\": {\n        \"chronology\": {\n            \"calendarType\": \"iso8601\",\n            \"id\": \"ISO\"\n        },\n        \"dayOfMonth\": 5,\n        \"dayOfWeek\": \"SATURDAY\",\n        \"dayOfYear\": 65,\n        \"era\": \"CE\",\n        \"leapYear\": true,\n        \"month\": \"MARCH\",\n        \"monthValue\": 3,\n        \"year\": 2016\n    },\n```\n\nfor `LocalTime`, it does no output time zone information.\n\n```\n    \"localTimeProperty\": {\n        \"hour\": 19,\n        \"minute\": 54,\n        \"nano\": 444000000,\n        \"second\": 44\n    },\n```\n\nMy questions are:\nIs the policy of output time zone information consistent? seems confused, especially for LocalDateTime.\nActually, i do not even know why javaers save LocalDate/LocalDateTime/LocalTime in db.\n(well, LocalTime seems be pure time, reasonable)\n"
